    "description": "Why do some stocks double in a day while others barely move? The secret lies in a metric called the 'float'. Here is how it works.",
    "datePublished": "2026-03-15"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is float in stocks?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The float is the number of a company's shares that are freely available to be traded by the public, excluding closely held or restricted shares owned by insiders."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is considered a low float stock?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Generally, a stock with a float of less than 10 to 20 million shares is considered a low float stock. These stocks are highly susceptible to extreme volatility."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does float affect stock price?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A low float means limited supply. If demand suddenly increases (due to news or hype), the limited supply of shares causes the price to gap up rapidly. High float stocks require much more money to move the price."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between outstanding shares and float?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Outstanding shares include every single share issued by the company, including those held by insiders that can't be sold. The float only includes the shares available for public trading."
